Prosper Loan Data Analysis¶

Yosmery Gonzalez¶

Introduction¶

The main purpose of this project is to use Python visualization libraries to systematically explore a selected dataset, starting from plots of single variables and building up to plots of multiple variables and producing a summary highlights showing trends and relationships discovered in the Loan Data from Prosper. Questions to be explored:

  • What factors affect a loans outcome status?. The variables to be considerred are as follows.
    • Employment status
    • IncomeRange
    • Prosper Score
    • Home owner status
    • Borrower State
  • What affects the borrowers APR or interest rate?
    • Loan original amount
    • Listing Category

Dataset Overview¶

The Loan Data from Prosper contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, borrower credit history, and the latest payment information.

#Understading Borrowers APR (The Borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR) for the loan)
def x_y_t(xL, yL, tittel, data):
    plt.figure(figsize=[4,4])
    plt.title(tittel)
    plt.xlabel(xL)
    plt.ylabel(yL)
    plt.hist(data)
    plt.show()

data = s_df['BorrowerAPR']
xL = 'BorrowerAPR %'
yL = 'No of borrower'
tittel = 'Borrower Annual Percentage Rate (%)'

x_y_t(xL, yL, tittel, data)

Observation: The Borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR) for the loan is concentarted between 0.15% and 0.2%. The distribution seems to be skweed to the right.

def cust_plot(df, xVar):
    plt.figure(figsize=[4, 4])
    plt.title(f'''Distribution of {xVar.title()}'''.title(), fontsize=10, weight='bold')
    plt.xlabel(xVar.title(), fontsize=10, weight='bold')
    plt.ylabel('Count'.title(), fontsize=10, weight='bold')
    sb.countplot(data=df, x=xVar, color=sb.color_palette()[0])
    plt.xticks(rotation = 90)
    plt.show()

# Example usage
df = s_df  # Replace with your DataFrame
xVar = 'EmploymentStatus'  # Replace with the column name you want to plot

cust_plot(df, xVar)

Observation: Employed clients have the most common type of employment

def x_y_t(xL, yL, tittel, data):
    plt.figure(figsize=[4,4])
    binsize = 500
    bins = np.arange(0, data.max()+binsize, binsize)
    plt.title(tittel)
    plt.xlabel(xL)
    plt.ylabel(yL)
    plt.hist(data)
    plt.show()

data = s_df['LoanOriginalAmount']
xL = 'Loan amount in $'

How employment and loans status impact the Borrower Rate?¶

#  Relationship across Rating, Loan Amount and Loan Status

plt.figure(figsize=(9,5)) 
sb.barplot(data=s_df, x='EmploymentStatus', y='BorrowerAPR',
           hue='LoanStatus', errorbar='sd', color=sb.color_palette()[0])

plt.xticks(rotation=40)

plt.show()

Observation:

  • It seems the main variables impacting Borrower APR are ProsperScore and ProsperRating with a negative correlation. ProsperScore seems to increase when BorrowerRate decrease
  • Another relevant find is that Loan Amount increases when Borrower APR increases.
  • The loan status current is correlated wiht high ProperScore. It seems that Borrowers APR decrease the higher the income range
  • It appears that the higher the ProperScore, the lower the borrower APR wiht current status and charge off as main loan status
  • It seems the borrower APR increases when borrowers are retired and self-employed. It also increase when borrowers do not own their home
  • It seems that most of the defaulted credits comes from individuals with low Prosper rating

Conclusions¶

Based on the visual analysis and answering the question posted in the introduction it is concluded that:

Employment status, income, home owner status are variables that appear to impact the loan outcome and Borrower APR. That means that clients that are full time employed, with average incomes and owners of homes are seen to obatianed a higher Proper Score that ultimalety allows then to get a current and completed loan.

It is also noticed that loan amonts are higher when the Proper Score is hig.

A statistical analysis and modelling is necessary after the Exploratory Data Analysis is underatken to make definitive assertions on the relationhsis and impacts of variables.
